attributes.descriptionHtml:
Hansel is a sweet boy who has come far from the day that he was surrendered to our care. He loves going for walks in wooded areas, rolling in the grass, and swimming in little pools or lakes. This loving dog is great with all animals big or small. Morning time is Hansel’s favorite time of the day. As soon as he wakes up he seeks out cuddles and genuinely looks forward to saying ‘good morning’ to you. Going for a trip to the dog park and getting lots of treats are the makings of a perfect day for this little man. Hansel is particularly fond of toys that squeak and always sniffs out spare slippers and socks to snuggle in bed with (yes he really cuddles with them). He loves sun naps and drags all his toys outside to take naps with him. This dog would be perfect for an outdoor enthusiast who is looking to add another dog to the family. Hansel will sleep all day if you let him, but when you bring him outside he unleashes all kinds of energy and joy. 

Due to the the world he grew up in, Hansel requires a week or two of patience for him to come out of his shell and show his true personality. He grows quite attached to whoever he bonds with. New environments are stressful for him but he adapts with praise and consistency. Hansel looks to other dogs in the home for guidance and confidence so having a doggie sibling or two in his adoptive home would be ideal. A calm and loving home will be best for our buddy but we think he'll do ok with older, quieter children too. Hansel is very attentive to his human's emotions and body language and would be an awesome addition to your family!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
In the summer of 2017, a truck driver dropped Penny off at Texas Litter Control in Spring, Texas, saying that he rescued her out of a nearby street. No one knows what kind of life she may have had  up to that point. TLC turned her over to a nearby Woodland's rescue. Penny was quickly adopted by a nice family but unfortunately, the family dog did not like her, so she was returned to the Rescue. Because this rescue has mostly large dogs, Penny was transferred to Emmy's Hope Rescue in October 2017,

Penny is very shy and nervous when she first meets new humans. She does not do well with busy, bouncy young children, loud noises and thunderstorms. Although she has made progress at the rescue with accepting new things, she continues to learn how to handle scary situations. Penny is very affectionate after she trusts you and she loves to sit in her favorite human's lap! However, she doesn't realize she's a "stretch", measuring about 40" from the tip of her nose to the tip of her tail! 

Penny needs to join a quiet family that doesn't have many visitors or young children to make her nervous. Penny needs a dog-loving family with lots of patience and experience working with dogs that need help developing their confidence and trust.

Estimated birth date: June 2014

Approximate weight: 28 lbs. 

If you would like to meet Penny, please call or text Stephanie at: 281-622-6549

*** ADOPTION  CRITERIA ***

To qualify to adopt from Emmy's Hope Rescue,

YOU MUST HAVE ALL 4 QUALIFIERS:

1. Live in the Houston area (no more than an hour's drive away).

2. Be 21 years or older.

3. Have a fenced yard. Fencing must touch the ground all the way around the yard.

4. We are looking for experienced pet owners. You must  have at least 2-3 years of good vet history, with your current and / or past dogs. Your vet record should show that you take your dog(s) to the vet annually for an exam and to update their Rabies and DHPP (distemper, parvo) vaccinations and heartworm testing, and that you purchase a monthly heartworm preventative.

 

INTERESTING DACHSHUND HISTORY ~

The Dachshund was created in Germany where it was known as the badger dog, dachs meaning badger and hund meaning dog. Illustrations of dogs resembling Dachshunds date to the 15th century, and documents from the 16th century mention the "earth dog," "badger creeper," and "dachsel." Badger wasn't the Dachshund's only prey. He was also used on den animals such as foxes, and packs of Dachshunds trailed wild boar. Those early Dachshunds varied greatly in size. The dogs used on badgers and boar weighed 30 to 35 pounds. Dachshunds used to hunt foxes and deer weighed 16 to 22 pounds, and smaller 12-pound Dachshunds hunted hares and weasels. For a brief time in the early 20th century, 5-pound Dachshunds were used to bolt cottontail rabbits.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Tori was recently interviewed to see why she hasn't been adopted.   Here is what she wants in a new home.
1. Love me as I will love you - unconditionally and forever.
2. Spend time with me. Exercise me daily
3. Feed me good food
4. Let me join in with all the family activities. I am a good girl and obedient.
5. I need at least one other playmate my energy level.
6.  I love water and would like nothing better than to play on the  beach in the waves.

Doesn't seem to be a tough list of requirements does it?

Tori is Brindle with the classic  face.  She is as sweet as she can be.  Tori loves to play but would like nothing better than to snuggle on the couch.  She insists on hugs, not kisses and will sneak a drink of unprotected coffee if you aren't watching!   

To ri is great with all her foster siblings from the smallest to the biggest. She follows behind her brothers and plays chase in the yard, or hide and seek in the house. She is going to make an awesome addition to any family.

Tori is cautious and shy.  She will need patience and love in her new home but once she has gained confidence she will be totally dedicated.

Please contact info@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online at www.aarfhouston.org/forms . Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet. Thank you for considering a rescue!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Theo is a gorgeous Brindle boy with a flash of white on his chest and a black face that just screams to be kissed.  Theo is a confident boy who loves to play in the yard with his siblings, or play tug with his siblings.  At the end of the day, before we go to bed, he has to have a snuggle with mom on the couch.  

As adorable as this boy is, he will be happiest with a sedate household that just want an adorable loving guy to snuggle with.  He will not be a running companion, nor will he do well with lots of stairs.  But Theo loves to go in the car and slow walks around the neighborhood.

Theo is anxious to learn and will be an awesome family member.  

He is best suited to a family with a yard.   He has grown up with Chihuahua's and larger dogs and is a very compassionate guy who plays gently with his friend who is special needs.   He was a bottle baby and has only known love and affection.
  
Theo has a depth perception problem so doesn't like to do stairs or cross over colors that he isn't familiar with. Like on walkway crossings.

Theo had a genetic defect and both of his back knees have had TPLO surgery to correct.  His right ankle fluxates, but there is nothing to be done with it.

 This young man is perfect. He loves to cuddle and lives his treats. Theo has the sweetest purring sound when he is playing with the other dogs. He sounds like a bull horn when he gets nervous. I cant imagine anyone could love this boy more than I do, but he is available for adoption to the right family who can care and love him.

  Please contact info@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online at www.aarfhouston.org/forms . Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet. Thank you for considering a rescue!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Flynn was born about October 4, 2014 and weighs about 22 lbs.  He is as cute as they come and was released from his puppy making days in a puppy mill in West Virginia.  The "millers" made a call to the humane society and said they no longer needed the services of 29 dogs and would they take them.  The shelter is a kill shelter due to space and could not handle so many dogs and so they asked if we would take them.  How could we not!  So, we squeezed and adjusted and were able to take them all.  Sadly, Flynn has failed two adoptions as after a decent length of time they still could not touch him nor would he stay in the same room as them.  He is wonderful with the other dogs here and is now considered a Joyful Rescues Sanctuary pet.  He can seldom be touched and if he is it is not for long and when we must "catch" him to be groomed we must use a towel to protect our hands because he will bite.  He does happily live inside the house with the humans who live and work here as long as they are not forcing themselves on him, which we do not unless absolutely necessary such as hair trimming.  It is felt Flynn is living his best life right where he is and is a very happy boy.  From Dr. Rasnake: There is mild pegmentary keratitis which is likely from hair rubbing on the surface of the eye.  This condition may be the result of improper hygiene/grooming.  His future family will need to be diligent to keep hair cut short around his eyes so this does not worsen.  He still can see, but there is some cloudiness. 

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility.  
Can't Adopt Me?  SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link "Special Instructions to Seller" if you want to note a particular pet

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Heath is a young dog and ready to be an ideal best friend and family dog. He has a naturally sweet and happy  temperament. He wants to hear you say "Good boy" a lot, so he will listen to what you want and then try his best to do it. He is full of life and friendliness and is going to love playing in your backyard and going for walks. Even better, he would be delighted to accompany you for jogs or hikes, or camping. He is good with most other dogs, however, he is very strong and likes to play a little rough. We have made sure he is all ready to go by getting him all his shots and a thorough vetting. He is ready to begin life with you and to show you what a good dog he is.
A SPECIAL NOTE TO YOU FROM HIS FOSTER:   Heath is a young healthy, housetrained dog who loves people, loves kids but may be too strong for younger children. He is a bit too interested in cats so probably better not to have any in his new home.  He is crate trained, takes treats  gently, and is smart as a whip. All ready knows sit, and paw and is working on come. Heath is a high energy dog and will need someone that can exercise him multiple times a day to keep him happy. He's just an overall good dog. 

Heath loves to play so a fenced yard is needed so he can run off all that energy! No cats and most likely only dog because of his energy.

Heath needs a very active family as he likes exercise!


If you are interested in Heath, please contact:

rorrcanine@gmail.com

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Mr. Jones has been living with his foster family for four months now (as of July 2021) and has made great progress with his social interactions. While still dog reactive to strange dogs, Mr. Jones behaves in a socially acceptable manner with this doggie foster brothers and sister. He is a people lover and wants to be near his people. He has been exposed to Apartment living when he is being baby sat by his human foster brother.  Caution is still needed with strange dogs, but one can pick him up and carry Mr. Jones away from the strange dogs.

 “Mr. Jones and me we’re gonna be big stars” goes the song by Counting Crow and that is what this dog wants to be, your star. Mr. Jones (Jonesy) Is a three-year-old, 20 lbs., fixed male; terrier mix with a moderate energy level. He has had no accidents at his foster home and will signal to be let out. Jonesy knows sit and down and his vocabulary includes “treat”, “dinner”, and “out”. He is working on shake and beg. He is very happy sitting with his people and being petted. He gets very excited for rides and walks.  The saddest part of Mr. Jones’s day is when he has to go to the kennel for the night. Jonesy would prefer to be in bed with his foster family.

Mr. Jones is looking for an adult family where he can be the only dog. He is dog reactive and care will need to be taken when he is around other animals. Jonesy is cautious around new people and experiences and may growl when he is nervous. High levels of excitement may also cause him to growl and/or snap at other animals. We are looking for a placement without children and that has a stable and predictable environment. This guy wants to be a good dog and will need gentle but consistent training to bring out his best. Is Mr. Jones the star for you?

Jonesy's adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives, plus a free basic obedience class at Cedar Run Pet Boarding & Daycare in Hiawatha. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, be altered and current on vaccinations and preventatives. Our adoption process includes reference and vet checks, a background check and a home visit.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Brody is a gorgeous white and fawn colored retriever mix who weighs about 65 pounds, is neutered, up to date on vaccines and microchipped. He is estimated to be about 5-6 yrs old. Brody gets along with other dogs but not interested in playing and is a little socially awkward. He is hesitant at first and will need time and patience from his new family. He will need a home that can work on his manners in a completely positive way and manage his quirky ways. A fully fenced in yard is Required as he is very skittish when walking outside of his comfort zone area. If you are looking for a walking partner or someone to take to the park he is NOT your dog. An experienced pet parent(s) is needed for Brody as he has some resource guarding issues that need to be monitored. He is a vocal dog and tries to communicate with sounds that can be misunderstood at first. He is the type of dog that needs time to trust his human before bonding and is leery of new situations. He has come a long way in his foster home but will need continued reinforcement and a very committed home. We believe older kids or no kids would be best for him since he is still learning boundaries. Preferably a low key home without a lot of visitors or activity.

 

Interested in adopting me?  To fill out an application visit 3 Hearts 4 Paws

attributes.descriptionHtml:
One of the first things people ask about Bentley is “What kind of dog is that?” given his unusual looks, followed by “What a dog!” given his incredibly bubbly personality. Such a unique dog must have an equally unique story and Bentley is no exception! Bentley’s story starts with him landing in a municipal shelter where this active and friendly dog had no outlet for his energy. He was then transferred to our partner organization, Save Our Strays, that saw the potential and drive in Bentley and started working towards getting him into a board and train facility that would benefit him. That’s where Adopt-A-Dog and Ernesto at DOGS 360 came in; to train and work with Bentley until we could find him a home. This program had Bentley working with both Ernesto and other dogs daily to help work on his manners and also provide much-needed socialization. The greatest boon is that this program was in a home environment, so Bentley got a foster experience while also becoming the dog we knew he could be.

Due to his stay at DOGS 360, Bentley has made great strides in his socialization skills as well as his manners. We learned that Bentley is a tug master who has plenty of canine friends. He is the ideal companion for a family that likes to be outdoors (he LOVES going for bike runs) and would be by your side on a hike. Bentley’s ideal future family would learn all the training he has learned and continue to give Bentley the structure and consistency he needs to flourish. For that reason, we would love to see Bentley in a home with older kids that could learn his training alongside him. He is a friendly and goofy dog that is waiting to become your next family member, so why not come and meet him today? You can’t say no to a face like that!



Contact the Adoptions team at (914) 273-1674 or adoptions@adoptadog,org for more information!

The first step to adopting one of our dogs is to fill out our online adoptions questionnaire located here: https://forms.gle/5heEH8S6c7zXBneD7

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Gracie, a Plott Hound, and her brother Angelo were left outside a Georgia shelter in horrible condition. Born in early 2017, Gracie was extremely emaciated when she came into rescue: at only 16 pounds, she was only half of what her body weight should have been and in addition, she had an ulcerated eye, demodex mange, anemia, parasites, was dehydrated, and her two rear paws were swollen and infected with puncture wounds there and on her neck. Gracie has made a full recovery and is searching hard for her forever home. We just don't understand why she is still in foster and has not been adopted yet! This young girl needs a home with another confident dog as she is submissive and timid. When first being introduced into your home, she may be scared and timid, but given her previous 'life' its no wonder! Her home should not have cats, and should be one where there is a fairly established routine. She absolutely thrives in a home where expectations do not change. Gracie is house trained, potty trained, leash trained and crate trained and in fact will seek out her crate when she feels nervous. If you have a loving home that fits this description and would like to adopt Gracie and give her a chance, please apply here: http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

 
RDR's adoption fees include the cost of spay/neuter/microchip at an RDR-approved facility, whether completed before adoption or if deferred because the pet is too young or has a medical issue.  All pets are also current on age-appropriate vaccines at the time of adoption.
 
Given technical constraints on this database, this pet's location may not be as listed here. We can, however, provide transport support for pets in foster at a considerable distance from the adopter.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Little C.J. belonged to a family since he was a puppy. He lived outside, most of the time, on a chain. At times he was allowed to run loose and play with several other dogs that also lived outside. One day he was part of a group that killed the owners’ 10 chickens. Not sure that C. J. actually attacked any chickens but because he was with the other bigger dogs, he was guilty by association. The man told his wife that all the dogs would be shot if she did not get rid of them. In 2017, the lady asked Emmy’s Hope Rescue to find C.J. a new home.

C.J. is a sweet, sweet little dog but he is extremely shy, especially when he first meets new people. We have been working on his socialization skills with unfamiliar humans and canines. C.J. is fine around cats. He has experienced so many new things since he came to Emmy's Hope that have helped him not be so fearful of everything. We recommend that C.J. be placed with a quiet family that will have the time and patience to continue helping him build his confidence and trust.

In October  2019,  C.J. was diagnosed with a moderate heart murmur. He does not need medication at this time and does not have any activity restrictions.

Estimated birth date:  January 2012
Approximate weight:  9 lbs.

If you would like to meet C J, please call or text Stephanie at: 281-622-6549.

*** ADOPTION  CRITERIA ***

To qualify to adopt from Emmy's Hope Rescue,

YOU MUST HAVE ALL 4 QUALIFIERS:

1. Live in the Houston area (no more than an hour's drive away).

2. Be 21 years or older.

3. Have a fenced yard. Fencing must touch the ground all the way around the yard.

4. We are looking for experienced pet owners. You must  have at least 2-3 years of good vet history, with your current and / or past dogs. Your vet record should show that you take your dog(s) to the vet annually for an exam and to update their Rabies and DHPP (distemper, parvo) vaccinations and heartworm testing, and that you purchase a monthly heartworm preventative.

History:
Yeti came to the Hermitage in December 2017 when a good samaritan found him. 

Personality:
Yeti is slowly beginning to trust people. He is making his way down to some of the cat trees where he can get more attention. He LOVES other cats and definitely should go home with his BFF beautiful little girl Hummingbird. Yeti is still a little shy but welcomes affection after a short introduction and will happily purr and rub up on your hand for more pets as long as you let him go at his pace. We are sure Yeti will continue to become more and more confident & trust the humans around him who just want to give him all the love he truly deserves. He needs a patient understanding new human to give him time to become the loving cat we all know he can be.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Monkey has scars all over her body, had a broken leg that we surgically repaired, and is sight impaired in one eye.  Despite the horrific treatment this sweet girl has previously endured, you will be hard pressed to find a sweeter dog.  Monkey was born around 5/17/15 and our best guess and is she a bully/lab mix.  She does great with adults, kids, and with other dogs who are not jumping on her (especially coming from her side with her impaired eye).  She is too interested in cats, so we think she would do best in a feline free home.  She loves attention and is quick to reward you with a smile, a hug, and maybe even a kiss.  If you are looking for a special furbaby that may not win a beauty pageant, come meet Monkey and watch her win your heart.  Monkey is in an Amazing Foster home and her family will tell you that this cutie is a real Doll!  Amazing Grace Bully Rescue is a foster based rescue in the Pensacola, Florida area. We do not have an actual facility and our fosters are spread all over the local area.  If you would like to meet any of our pups, the first step is to complete our online application and we will contact you as soon as we can.

Our adoption fee for Monkey is completely sponsored to an approved home.  Monkey is already spayed, current on shots and rabies, and microchipped.

If you would like to adopt this Amazing dog, please fill out our online adoption application at www.amazinggracebullyrescue.org

If you have any questions, feel free to call/text us at (850) 723-2037.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Bear is a super special pup. He is very shy and will likely always have a timid personality due to his early life and lack of proper socialization. He needs an owner with lots of patience that is just looking to help a dog with fear issues with new people. He does get attached to his special people as he is with his foster mom, but it can take some time to get there. He's a home body, loves to just play in his own securely fenced yard and he LOVES all other dogs. He would be a great companion for another dog and someone that lives a calm life. He would be too fearful of young children, but could befriend a teenager with a sweet nature.

If Bear might find a special place in your compassionate heart, he'd love to join a family and put down some real roots. Email placement@duckteam6.org if you would consider giving Bear a chance.

This handsome brindle boy is Dre! Born in 2012, Dre looks like a Boxer/Pit mix on a Boston Terrier frame...he really is the cutest little lowrider! He was rescued from a high kill NYC shelter where he found himself moments from euthanasia. Dre is wonderful with people of all ages and other dogs. No cats for him. Dre would do best with someone who is retired, or works from home, as he has separation anxiety. Dre takes medication daily for arthritis and does have some accidents in the home. He's waiting to be your new best friend.  If you would like to make Dre the love of your life, please fill out an adoption application here: http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org/general-application    

 

RDR's adoption fees include the cost of spay/neuter/microchip at an RDR-approved facility, whether completed before adoption or if deferred because the pet is too young or has a medical issue.  All pets are also current on age-appropriate vaccines at the time of adoption

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Peaches Goodman was born about November 18, 2010 and weighs about 32 lbs.  She is a pretty girl with rough coated fur in the white/grey/black range.  She is back with us after being gone for a few years - sadly, her human dad has passed away and her human mom is very ill.  Peaches has some reluctance to us reaching for her quickly and when you have company she is distrustful of humans coming into her home and will need to be crated or put in a separate room.  She is wonderful with the humans that she knows and trusts.  Peaches has a nice energy for her age and is pretty good on leash and enjoys the activity.  She is wonderfully house trained.  Overall, sadly she is an anxious girl and needs a human(s) that will satisfy her energy needs and someone that lives in a rather calm lifestyle without a lot of other humans coming and going.  She shivers and can get barky when she is stressed and when going in the car a Benedryl has been beneficial.  Peaches does well with the other dogs here. In April 2019 she was diagnosed with mammary carcinoma with a life expectancy of 1-2 years, but if that special human doesn't come along she will be loved and cared for here for whatever time she has left.  (7/2021 guess that vet was wrong- she is still doing well!)
Update:  After Peaches failed two foster homes we are considering her a JR sanctuary pet.  Did you know that there are very special dogs and cats who call Joyful Rescues home?
Peaches is what some may call “un-adoptable .”
Joyful Rescues remains committed to our Sanctuary Dogs and Cats. They will stay with us for their natural lives and we will care for and love them. We will be their forever family.
We wish we could do it alone but we need your help. We are looking for people who can help us with Peaches care. Please click the link below and donate. Peaches thanks you.

https://www.paypal.com/donate

 

 
Can't Adopt Me?  SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link "Special Instructions to Seller" if you want to note a particular pet

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Casanova will be your best friend! He is a large 5 year old Mixed breed lover. Casanova loves to play with you and his toys, he loves to be right by your side, and he loves to chew on his nylabone for down time. He would do best in a home with no cats or small dogs. Needs slow introductions to larger dogs. Would do best with older children 12+.  He is such a sweet boy who loves to give you kisses & did we mention how much of a gentleman he is on a leash? Casanova would love his own furever home, after having a rough life having ended up in the shelter with Heartworms to be shortly on death row. Casanova was rescued and now is all healthy, up to date on his shots, and neutered. Casanova is such a sweet boy and would love a family to call his own! Won't you give him a chance?

All adoptable dogs have been medically cleared by our attending veterinarian at Clear Lake Animal Hospital, up to date on vaccines, spayed or neutered and microchipped. All dogs currently on heartworm and flea/tick prevention and parasite free. His adoption fee is $250

Application to adopt must be filled out here- https://www.kol-fl.org/adopt/adoption-application/

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Sparten is such a cutie but he is still a timid little pup.  He is going to need someone with a lot of patience.  He, and his sister, Stella, are parvo survivors which is awesome.  He will need to go into a home with another dog.  He really likes to go out and play chase in the backyard with his sister.  He will need a home with a yard.  I don't think an apartment will work for either of them.  If he can't go outside to play they will run up and down the stairs to run their energy off.  He loves to give kisses and he will sit in your lap for short periods of time.   We are working on socialization and we are about half way to getting potty training done.  He is crate trained and know how to sit and shake hands.  With proper introduction he gets along with other dogs.  It is also recommended he go to a family with kids 10 years old or older.  He jumps a lot and even though he is small to medium in size he can still knock you over if you are not paying attention.

Please contact  app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application . Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue!

attributes.descriptionHtml: My name is Rosie, I'm five years old and this is my story. I lived with a person who was not able to take care of me, so he left me on the side of a road. I did not know how to survive outside, so after a short time, I became dehydrated and emaciated. A kind person found me, took me in and nursed me back to health. In spite of what happened to me, I have a special personality. I'm extremely affectionate and I love people. My favorite thing to do is cuddle with someone I love. attributes.descriptionHtml:
NOEL is beautiful, young, carefree, energetic and very loving girl who just wants to have fun!  She LOVES playing with the other dogs, going on walks, or just generally doing whatever her family is doing.  She's going to make someone a FANTASTIC buddy and companion!

TEMPERAMENT
Noel is amazing.  She was seized for extreme cruelty - starved, dehydrated, and out in the elements with no shelter from the cold, wet, or heat.  But despite her suffering at the hands of a few heartless humans, she still LOVES people and can't get enough of you!  She's one of those dogs that just make you grin watching her exuberance and zest for life.  She's a sweet little girl who LOVES her people. She's learning basic manners and doing very well, so we think she'll be easy to train.  The first new behavior she had to practice was waiting at baby gates or backyard fences -- and she wanted to follow her person so badly that she climbed the fence simply to go sit next to her person on the other side!  With a 6 ft fence she will be fine.  With a somewhat lover fence, she will need complete supervision until  in the backyard to avoid escaping.  . 

She's learning crate manners and was much happier once she discovered her crate had a nice soft bed! She groans a little when put in her crate -- you know, like the child who groans when it's bedtime? -- but then settles down.  She has also learned to wait to be released.  She's learning quickly and is proving to be quite a sweetheart with a nice balance of patience and energy. 

Overall, Noel is joy-on-four-legs and therefore a joy for us humans to be around and watch!

OTHER ANIMALS
Noel must have a doggie buddy to play and romp with!  She gets along well with other dogs and has energy to burn.  She has lived with all large dogs and romped happily, chasing and being chased.  Her current foster home has 1 large dog and 2 small dogs and she does great with all of them.  She's very excited to play and plays nicely even with the dogs a quarter of her size.  She's still got a lot of puppy in her and occasionally doesn’t notice when the small dogs tell her they're tired, so you may have to remind her that play time is over.  But she takes correction easily and is perfectly willing to go inside and let the other dogs rest.  Noel has a mild-to-moderate small prey drive and can not be in a home with cats.

KIDS
Noel has not yet been tested with kids.  We believe her only issue will be that of any large, strong and energetic dog:  the potential to be too rough in play and knock a child over, or collide with a child.  As with all large dogs, she must be supervised around small children just to be sure things don't get too rough.

MEDICAL
Noel is a healthy, strong youngster with a long life ahead of her.  She was originally heartworm positive but has been treated and is heartworm free.

DOGS:    Does well with large and small dogs! (currently lives with 1 large and 2 small dogs)
CATS:     No cats (mild-to-moderate prey drive)
KIDS:      Not tested yet, believe will do well with supervision to prevent accidents
IDEAL FAMILY:   An active family with at least one other dog and a 6 ft fence (strongly recommended).  A family who will spend the time to exercise her and stimulate her, and finish her training using good canine leadership skills.

If you're looking for a gorgeous, young, trainable furball
who will love you forever,
NOEL is your girl!


NOEL'S ADOPTION FEE:   $300
This fee covers only part of what we spend to vet, board and rehab the dogs we save. On average we spend over $450 on each dog. We made a decision to keep our adoption fee at the 2005 level even though vet prices have doubled and tripled since then. We are constantly fundraising to cover the deficit. At minimum, your adoption fee includes the dog's spay/neuter, heartworm test, heartworm treatment if needed, rabies shot, distemper/parvo shot, bordatella shot, deworming, monthly heartworm and flea preventives, and microchip. In many cases it also includes surgery and various types of vet treatment for standard issues such as hot spots, ear infections and so o

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Personality:   

None of our foster dogs are tested with cats because we have no way of testing them with cats. Siberians are notorious for their high prey drive and typically kill cats, rabbits, chickens, birds, squirrels, opossums, etc., so we we don't have much success adopting them out to homes with cats. Most of our foster dogs are with us for killing cats, chickens and goats to begin with so our assumption is they are not good with cats and other small things that move. 

Siberians are typically good with children of all ages and the only reason we would not list them as not good with kids is because they may be too energetic and bouncy and knock over a toddler.

Southern Siberian Rescue is a volunteer based 501(c)3 organization based out of Raleigh, NC, so we do not have a physical facility with operating hours that you can visit to meet our dogs. All of our foster dogs are in our personal homes. You need to fill out our adoption application (http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption) and get approved to adopt and then we will set a time for you to meet our foster dogs. As a volunteer based group, we all have jobs, family, personal dogs and other commitments but we try to acknowledge and process applications as quickly as we can. That being said, we try to keep our available foster dogs as current as we can also but it is time consuming to get pics and information on new dogs so not all of our dogs are listed at all times. Please fill out our application and then we can discuss dogs that will work for you and your situation. We average 40-45 Siberians in our program so we are certain we have one that will work for you. Please know that we are not obligated to answer inquiries on dogs as we will focus on approved applicants. Again, there is ample time to discuss all of our foster dogs AFTER we have an approved application on file. We do adopt out of state as long as we can get a home check done. We ask that you, your family and existing pets make the trip to NC to meet and adopt our foster dogs. 

SSR can not and will not hold dogs for anyone. If we do, that means another Siberian will die in a shelter because a shelter dogs time is very limited, as is our foster space. We do our best to process applications in the order received and first application gets first interest in our foster dog(s). We understand that there will be scheduling conflicts with home checks and meet and greets but we will try to accommodate for that if a potential adopter has interest in a particular foster dog in our program.

All Southern Siberian Rescue foster dogs are microchipped, up to date on shots, spay/neutered, on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative. For additional information on Southern Siberian Rescue and Siberian Huskies, please visit www.SouthernSiberian.com. To fill out an application, please visit http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption .
attributes.name: Willow
attributes.sponsorshipDetails: We will always accept sponsor monies for our foster dogs. You can Paypal us at SouthernSibes@yahoo.com or mail a check to SSR, PO Box 98601, Raleigh, NC 27624. Thank you in advance for considering a sponsorship.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Hi my name is Duke. I have been at the shelter for three years now.  In that time I have made great strides in my training. I am extremely friendly with the staff who work and care for me everyday.   I am becoming a very good car rider. I am unsure of new people I meet and require extra time to build trust with new people.  An owner who understands this is a must for me. Some of the things I enjoy include going on long walks, having a game of fetch, (still working on releasing the ball), rolling on my back with or without snow, enjoying a good beef bone, tossing my kennel blankets up in the air, chasing butterflies, bees, and even leaves blowing in the air on a windy day and getting a good back massage.  Because I have demonstrated great intelligence, staff occasionally have me practice obedience exercises along with using my nose to search for treats. I can sit and stay and am currently working on a couple of agility skills.  I have gotten along with some of the dogs here at the shelter and would be willing to meet yours.  Hope this information helps and the right person comes to take me home. Woof, Duke

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Meet Stu! He's a great dog with a big heart and whose favorite things to do is cuddle and receive belly rubs. He can be playful too so a fenced yard would be a plus but is not required, with a couple quick walks each day he does just fine. Stu currently lives with two other dogs and is fine most of the time "occasionally rude to male" but he does not do well with cats. He is food reactive and would do best in a home with kids 13 yrs. or older. He has some separation anxiety but that has been easy managed with proper medication. Stu is very well socialized with people, is eager to please and is food motivated. He is smart and responds well to training. He knows sit, wait, release command (“okay”) and does well on a harness lead for walks. He is about 6.5 years old and crate and house trained.

Stu’s adoption fee is $175; he is neutered, microchipped, and up-to-date on all of his vaccines. If you are interested in meeting Stu, please contact us at adoption@ihadro.org or, you can find an adoption application at www.ihadro.org/forms
attributes.name: Stu

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Shelly, a beautiful Pittie, was rescued from Manhattan ACC where she had been brought in as a stray, with broken teeth and was emaciated at only 24 pounds!!  She is thought to have been born in 2015.  Her foster mom has been taking such good care of her and despite her obvious neglect, Shelly remains a very sweet and loving girl, she  is super smart and would do well in a suburban home with a fenced yard and an active family who can devote time to her and to make sure she gets enough of her favorite activity. . . chasing tennis balls!  She  is great with kids and people of all ages. She does not do well with cats, and slow introductions are required if there are other dogs in the home. Shelly   is spayed, up to date on vaccinations, housebroken, crate trained and knows basic commands.  Please apply online if you are interested in adopting Shelly: http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Loki
4 yo male
60 pounds
Fawn
Dog & Kid Friendly
Crate & Leash Trained
Fostered in Dayton, Or

 

Loki, Loki, not so slow poky!

I know what your thinking when you read the name Loki. Rest assured, Loki is no villain!

Loki is an easy-going, loving cuddle buddy. The sweetest non-villain you'll ever meet. Loki is laid-back, goes with the flow most of the time although loves to play. Loves to greet you at the door and jumps for joy, then turns around, lays in your lap for some good'ole relaxing TV time.

Loki is taking in a whole new world with his foster family. They are a little more active then the family he came from. A little more chaotic with kids and other dogs but he's adjusting well and learning there's more out in the world than he thought.

While it's all a little overwhelming and some times this can make him nervous, he seeks assurance from his family and doggie pals. He is quick to learn, eager to please and loves to fit in. Patience helps him build confidence to discover new things, going places, trying new activities and such. He truly is a big teddy bear learning how to love life and embrace all that is around.

Do you have time, love, patience and an open heart to share with Loki? Please apply today at:

https://www.nwboxerrescue.org/adoption-form



If you would like to adopt him, fill out an adoption application on our website www.nwboxerrescue.org

Like us on facebook for more photos of this handsome boy, as well as other boxers we have available!  www.facebook.com/northwestboxerrescue

attributes.descriptionHtml: Alika here (“most beautiful” in Swahili). My foster mom named me not just based on my show-stopping forever puppy eyes, but on my heart. That is where my true beauty lies (don’t get me wrong, I’m a very cute pocket pitty too). I absolutely adore children!!! In fact, I love all people! I like to follow my people around and give them all of my love. I’d be an excellent companion for someone working from home or just someone who wants to be greeted with a giant smile and wiggle butt when they come home. I’m an adult so I already know all of my house manners and commands (I’ve even had some formal training!). I occupy myself well playing with my toys but I’m over all that puppy energy and mischief. I just want to be your best friend and have a home of my very own!  Alika is up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, spayed, microchipped, and on heartworm prevention. Alika’s adoption fee is $200.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Beethoven is the perfect age for a pit bull at around 6 years old. He is smart, house trained, crate trained and fantastic in the car. He is good on a leash and would do just about anything for a treat or a tennis ball. Beethoven is deaf but that doesn't slow him down. If anything he is more attentive than hearing dogs because he looks to his person for direction. Beethoven knows sign language and is a velcro dog: wherever his person is, that is where he wants to be. Beethoven loves the water and will spend hours splashing in a baby pool. This sweet guy would make a great running buddy or agility dog. Beethoven would prefer to be the only 4 legged member of your family! His favorite spot is on the couch..... UNDER the blankets! Looking for a couch buddy??? Apply to adopt Beethoven today!
Beethoven is neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped and heartworm tested and on preventative. His adoption fee is $200. 
To apply to adopt Beethoven, visit www.adoptapitrescue.org/apply

attributes.descriptionHtml: Hiya! My name is Evie.  I'm 6 years old and my foster mom says I am the sweetest, most special girl. I have been in the rescue a loooooong time because until very recently I was scared of everything. The nice ladies in the rescue took me in when I was 4 months old and I won't tell them what happened to me before that, but it was bad and I was so scared. A few months ago I had the opportunity to go see this wonderful trainer named Alicia and she helped me and my foster momma learn how to deal with my fear and anxiety and now I'm doing so much better! My momma challenges me every day and I'm finally learning how to act like a dog (and not a scaredy cat)! I love to play and run in the yard now with my foster siblings and sprawl out on the couch and chew a bone. I still like my crate, but I like to be outside of it now too! I am still a little timid when meeting new people, but I will bark while checking them out instead of running to hide, and you can win me over with cheese!  If you can show Evie love and patience, please apply! She deserves a forever home to call her own! Evie's adoption fee is $200.  She is up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, spayed, microchipped, and on heart worm prevention.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Lilith likes to play with toys on a string with her person and will happily play and swat cat toys around on her own! Lilith is a girl who knows exactly what she wants and how things should be - and will make sure that you know! She likes to be petted - but will let you know when it is time. She likes to sit on you - but will let you know when it is time. Lilith is desperately missing a moderately calm home where she can be with people that are hers. She lost her human Daddy just before the Christmas of 2016. The trauma of losing her home and her daddy send her into extreme despair! She quit eating and had to have a feeding tube! This little girl is no quitter. She recovered and is doing well in her foster home, but really wants her very own home! She would do best in a home with no other cats. 

To learn more or to be pre-approved for adoption please contact us at: catnetwork.org

attributes.descriptionHtml: Tesla is a sleek and gorgeous black girl who is very affectionate and playful.  She has a sensitive soul and seeks a best friend who will dote on her and understand how she likes things.  She loves to play and give affection but can become worried easily, so is best in a home without other pets or small children (although she will tolerate other gentle cats or dogs). Tesla will sit on your lap and loves petting but if she gets overstimulated will play bite and grab her person, so she needs someone who can stop playing when needed and redirect her.  She is a really special girl who will be a wonderful best friend to a person looking for a sensitive soul to spend some quality time with.  Are you the lucky person for her?  For more info contact jmclaug@me.com

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Rainey is an extremely social cat. Her favorite things are petting and watching the bird feeder that hangs outside a window. She loves petting and will “drop and roll” to show her belly when she wants attention and will also seek out a lap when wanting to be close. Her sister Breezy (Bengal Tabby) is Rainey’s favorite playmate.  Both kitties love interactive play and are compatible playmates.  Having a pair of cats that are good playmates is a healthy alternative to a sedentary lifestyle for indoor cats.

 

Visit our website at: www.animalnetwork.org to see our fees, adoption requirements and to view other available animals we have for adoption. Email: contact@animalnetwork.org for the application to adopt and tell us a little about your family’s lifestyle and home. Some of the new arrivals can be seen in the caregiver’s homes on weekdays. A mandatory pet parenting class is given on Saturdays so you can learn how to introduce your new pet to existing ones, teaching house manners, recommended foods and the best litter, and what you can do to avoid your cat from getting certain diseases. If you can’t find the pet that you are looking for sign up for our “Pet Match Service” and tell us what you are looking for. A $25 donation is accepted for this 1 year service.
attributes.name: Rainey (Like The Jazz Singer)

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Looks AND voice!!  Nick is a stunning little house leopard with the personality of a teddy bear.  Nick was born in the summer of 2017 and lives with his foster mom Robin.  He loves to play with the other cats and snuggle his foster mom at night.  He may be a little shy on the first date, but give him time and he can be your best bud!  

He has tested negative for FIV/Felv, has had worm and flea treatment and his distemper shots. He has been neutered and has his rabies shot. His adoption donation is $65.

If you are interested in Nick, please call or text Robin at 717-612-2840. 

Thank you for considering the adoption of a rescued cat! Loving Care Cat Rescue is a No-Kill organization that helps cats in need. There are Loving Care foster homes throughout southcentral PA helping unwanted cats and kittens find new forever homes.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Frankie (Monkey Man) is a darling, tiger and white male, born 11/9/17. Poor little guy was left in a box on the side of the road with his brother on Christmas Eve 2017 in the bad weather when he was a tiny kitten. Frankie has some back end weakness left over from chronic toxoplasmosis that he was previously treated for. Frankie is also believed by our vets to have some neurological issues...sort of making him much like a human with mild mental retardation but that's what makes him sooo cute!. He has also had to overcome a lung infection and has been doing much better now. Frankie is a sweet & happy boy that will need slow acclimation to a new home and a very patient adopter. He does have some potty issues but its getting better and He plays a little rough at first, but that has much improved. He enjoys playing with other young cat. He is obsessed with those little coil/spring cat toys. Also check out his video! Please e-mail Karin at pa4gbodine60race@aol.com if you would love to welcome him into your family. He is current on vaccines, neg. for FeLV/FIV & neutered. His adoption fee is $125.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Welcome to Cats Meow Dogs Bark Rescue, is an all volunteer animal welfare and rescue organization! Animals listed on our websites and other adoptable websites are available for adoption at our adoption house; Pounce & Fetch (512 Southview Blvd South St. Paul, MN 55075), we have no set hours, but we are always there cleaning and caring for the animals that reside at Pounce & Fetch! Please be aware of our sign on our front door. It will ask that you "Please knock, we are here cleaning" when you are more then welcome to come in and help us and visit the animals. Should it read "We are closed" means that we are not ready to receive guests and perhaps call to schedule at time or wait till the sign is flipped. To start the journey of adopting a new family member from Cats Meow Dogs Bark Rescue you'll need to complete our adoption application. It is the first step toward possibly adding a new member to your family. You can either stop in at Pounce & Fetch to pick up and complete it or email us at adoptablepets@aol.com and we will send you the form, please complete and return via email.  Unanswered question could delay your application. Please don't be intimidated by our Adoption Application, its purpose in genuine. We have kept it simple for a reason so that we can get to know you and your family so that we can assist you with finding the right pet to join your family, forever! Sadie is a beautiful 3 1/2  year old girl! She is Border Collie, Golden Retriever & Cocker mix. She is 45 lbs. Sadie is loving and a very active girl. She enjoys being with humans BUT NOT other animals. Sadie could not go in a dog park with other dogs. She needs to be the only pet in the home. You'll love Sadie!!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Although we do our very best to make sure your new pup is in tiptop health before adoption, things could drastically change a month later.  Since we don’t have a long health history of your adopted dog, we can only treat her for whatever symptoms that present during the initial exam and follow up exams. - -

Health: When Bubbles first came into our rescue (early 2018) a benign mass was removed from her neck. She also was successfully treated for heart worms and numerous parasites.  This girl was very sick when we first received her. 

*****On April 24th, she was diagnosed with an enlarged heart.  She is on Lasix and Enalapril twice a day for the rest of her life. Initially it was difficult to administer her medication. She now enjoys her medication when it is put into a small bit of liverwurst and offered as a "treat".  *****    No other obvious health issues have been diagnosed. - -


Temperament: She has only been used for breeding, so she is more comfortable being with dogs than people.  It will take some time and patience for her to learn that people can be nice.  If you decide to adopt Bubbles, I hope you will consider that it will take some time before she becomes the lap dog you might be hoping for.   Bubbles has been seriously mistreated her whole life.  She is not going to trust you immediately.  Please don't apply to adopt her unless you are very serious about putting in the time it will take to help her adjust to a "normal" dog life.  -----------------------------------------------------------

She has never bitten anyone but she does run from you when she is outside and she will back herself into a corner when you reach for her inside.  When you reach down to pick her up, she will throw her front paws up in the air and it almost looks like a small child reacting to someone picking them up.   It would be funny except that she does it out of fear.   I believe it will take a very long time for bubbles to relax and enjoy being part of the family. She will not be easy but it will be very rewarding when she comes to you for a treat and to enjoy some ear scratching for the first time. Update 7/1/2019 Bubbles still retreats if you go to get her; however, she is starting to come and laydown and relax near her foster family daily especially if another dog is already there. She likes to be on the sofa and bed and will use dog steps to get up and down from the bed.  --------------------------

Bubbles knows how to use a doggie door.  She is crate trained as well.  She is walking very well on a leash hooked to her collar or harness.  She likes the harness the best and it's the safest way to walk her.  She is most cooperative when walking alongside other confident dogs but she will walk by herself too.  She will just be more on alert. 

Where did she come from: She came from puppy mill closure.  It was a really awful place. ——

Adoption: $324.75 ($300.00 fee + $24.75 required 8.25% sales tax)
Weight: 9 lbs.
DOB:  2/8/2009 

ADOPTION APPLICATION: http://www.recycledpoms.org/application
 
Email info@recycledpomeranians.com to request a printable application.
 
------Please remember our group is made of only volunteers all of whom have full time jobs, foster fur-kids, and families of their own, so please be patient.---------

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Look at this pudgy little face. Makes you want to pinch his little cheeks. But get to know this little guy first. It's not that he isn't a great dog; he is! He just takes a little time to warm up to people. And when he does, it is such a great feeling because he loves with all his little heart. His foster mom says it is so sweet to see him seeking love and accepting attention. 

Meet Sisco! Sisco is an almost 7-year-old, 16-pound, neutered male Chihuahua mix. He has a gorgeous, short, tan and white coat. He is house and crate trained (but his foster says Sisco spent too much time in a crate prior to his rescue, and he is fine out of his crate—so, she seldom crates him).  And he walks very nicely  on-leash  but will pull a little. Because Sisco wasn't socialized when younger, he tolerates other dogs but doesn't really interact. So Sisco will make a great only dog.

Sisco will need a patient adopter who will give him time to adjust to a new environment, and he will reward you by bestowing his love and allowing you to see him blossom into a sweet, loving, little guy.  Sisco does have diabetes, but his condition is easily treated by insulin shots twice a day.  And he does well with little ones who are good with dogs; he seems fascinated by them and follows them around (but supervise them so Sisco doesn't get hurt).  

You can apply to adopt Sisco at the website shown below. 

 

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms 

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.
attributes.name: Sisco

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Mishi is a black female kitten who was trapped by Amy Zane in her yard.  Amy fostered Mishi and her 2 siblings (Mila & Bootsie).  

Mishi
Mishi was the third and last of her litter to brave approaching her fosterers.    Her fosterers sat out in one of the coldest November days trying to coax her with yummy food.    After many hours they were ready to leave    and give up for the day and just then Mishi went into the carrier to start her new life.    During her time in    foster care she has been the same way- holding out for long periods but then giving in at the last minute. She is worth every single moment of waiting though.    She has a remarkable calming presence and loves cuddling once she’s accustomed to her surroundings.    She is even more likely to want to lay quietly being pet if her person is singing softly or willing to rub her shoulders.   Her favorite song is "Bring your love to me" by the Avett Brothers, sung emotively- it's her favorite.

Mishi loves to play with toys- and especially likes bigger soft kitty toys that she can carry into her bed and sleep with.     She has hidden talents too.    Her fosterers were confounded repeatedly because her water bowl would be so low after filling it just a short time before but after asking her so many times why her bowl was so low she showed them how she would rear up and come down with both legs into the water in order to make the biggest splash of droplets as she could so she could then leap up to try to catch them.    She was doing cat “cannon balls” in the water bowl all in the name of fun!    She now plays with other toys instead of her water bowl but she maintains her playfulness despite her otherwise quiet demeanor.    She is a real character always doing the unexpected in the name of sport so her new owners will have to spend time playing as well as giving in to her demands for cuddling time.

  In a new home Mishi will hide at first if given the opportunity.    She does best starting in out in a smaller more confined area then being allowed into new rooms gradually.    In foster care she enjoyed a cat hammock but a cat tree with a hidey-hole or some other area off the ground in a small room would give her the most confidence at first.    Mishi’s person(s) will need have patience and be willing to put in time to gain her trust and not take her tendency to hide personally.    Consistency is important with her.     She will    need continual positive experiences until she gains her confidence in a new environment.    After that hurdle she will seek out attention and be perfectly happy to cuddle up next to you or on top of you whenever she has the opportunity to do so.    She will be just as outgoing as any other lovey kitty if she is allowed to go through her routine of slow exploration and acclimation.     

Mishi did enjoy her siblings and would be happy to go home with one or both of them but barring that would do well with another feline or a lazier dog after a slow introduction but she will still need some amount of one on one interaction with her people daily.
attributes.name: Mishi

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Mila is a black female kitten who was trapped by Amy Zane in her yard along with 2 other siblings (Bootsie & Mishi).  

Mila
 
Mila has a very sweet disposition and is very fond of laps.     She would be fantastic in a home where people sit to binge watch their favorite shows or read.    She will likely spend a lot of time next to you with her arm and head draped over your leg or completely curled up on your lap.    And she’s happy to nap right alongside you if you happen to doze off.    Mila’s ideal home would be one where she is allowed to sleep in the bed with her people.    She is willing to share with another pet as well.    If Mila could speak human language she would learn the word for “lap” from every country.   
If your lap is not available she is happy to explore and make her own fun.    She likes sitting in a window looking at birds or playing with any kind of toy.     if you go away for a little vacation she will do fine on her own or with her furry friends making her own fun but upon your return she’s going to be waiting for you to sit for her so she can claim your lap again.  
 
Mila is a stunning looking cat with her long legs and sleek coat.  She used to enjoy laying upside down in her cat hammock with her head drooping lazily out of the hammock as if to say, "yes, I am the epitome of catness.  Know me and understand why mankind has worshipped my fellow catkin since the time of the Ubastet!"  In short, Mila thinks she's royalty and you are there to serve her.  She will treat you well if you do indeed show her adoration and allow her all the time she needs to laze with you.
attributes.name: Mila

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Due to COVID-19 we are currenty modifying our adoption process.  In order to safeguard exposure to the virus, all our cats are in foster homes.  Complete and Submit the Adoption Application online, include the pet's name (NO NUMBERS).  If the pet is available, and your Adoption Application is approved or being considered, an AAS representative will call you.

Birthdate: October 2017

UPDATE September 2018

I CAN'T  BELIEVE I'M STILL WAITING FOR MY 4EVER HOME!!!

I'm comparing my situation to that little "red dot" on the laser pointer toy.  As hard as I try to get it - it's still out of reach - just like my 4ever home!

Come on guys - I'm the coolest cat in town from my amazing personality to my handsomely unqiue face - I've definitely got it going on!

My 1 year birthday is next month and the best gift I could ask for would be to catch that "red dot" with you.  Can someone out there prove to me that wishes do come true?

 

Hello Everyone

I'm Graffiti a black and white charmer with a funny face and a personality to match.

You know, sometimes a cat is one solid color and other times they're a mixutre of colors.  But, I have something different.

My markings are very unusual with spots and smudges creating all sorts of weird and amusing patterns on my face.  It's just like human birthmarks but for me it's "furmarks".  I think it gives me character!

If I could get dressed up, I'd have a red rubber nose, a rainbow colored wig and big floppy shoes - cause I'm just like a clown. I'm a lovable guy with an outgoing goofy, silly and playful personality.

I love my toys and I think that all toys are wonderful, including homemade ones like paper balls, straws and anything that crinkles.  

I'm great with other cats and I have lots of feline friends in my foster home.

If you're ready for some fun and laughter in your life, it's easy to meet me.  Simply complete an online adoption application and ask for Graffiti the "clown".

You can fill out an application for GRAFFITI at the Aventura  Petsmart or go to www.adoptastray.ws/applications/ to fill out an application online or print and fax one to (954) 965-0406.

Petsmart employees are not familiar with the cats available through Adopt A Stray.  Please contact Adopt A Stray directly.

Learn more about Adopt A Stray by visiting our website www.adoptastray.ws.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Reina will be a forever foster in DRM's Program, however we would work with the right forever home for this sweet girl.

 

Meet Reina! This girl is just 3 years old and is handicapable!

Reina was originally rescued from a high kill shelter by an all breed rescue. It was apparent she suffered from neurological issues, but nothing could be found on x-rays of her spine. DRM then stepped in and welcomed Reina into our program to get the help needed so she can thrive!  

Reina was born with a condition that caused the nerves from her back legs to brain to not map completely. Sometimes she can be a bit wobbly and sometimes she suffers from incontinence. She is on a special diet that has helped a lot with her potty issues though! 

Reina’s favorite activities include snuggling her humans, chewing on bones, going for walks, playdates with her friends and exploring the yard. She also LOVES to chase rabbits and squirrels! When she’s tuckered out, she’ll sunbathe looking out the window or hang out with her foster family. 

Reina has lived with other dogs and cats – she’s awesome with dogs but can be very curious about her feline friends. Reina is super smart and knows all the basic commands. Her recall is great (as long as she’s not scouting for bunnies or squirrels) and she is very food motivated to learn anything else you’d like to teach her. She is a hit around the neighborhood with her sunny disposition and love of everyone she meets. 

Reina would do best in a home where someone would be home with her most of the day – she loves to snuggle! She loves everyone she meets so she’s not picky – she just needs someone to make her world complete. Could that be you? 

This fabulous foster is a Doberman Rescue Minnesota foster dog.

Please read all adoption steps and policies carefully on our website. http://dobermanrescueminnesota.com/adoption-steps/

Qualified adopters are within the approved adoption area, and Adopter will be requested to visit this foster dog at the foster family home. Our foster families are generally located within a 250 mile radius of Minneapolis, MN.

All DRM dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, health checked, microchipped, dewormed, 4DX tested, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Date into Rescue: 2/21/2018 - Lacey was adopted in 2018 but in December of 2020, the family of Lacey's owner contacted us. Their mother could no longer care for Lacey and they were not able to provide a home either. Lacey returned to us 12/30/20.  
Reason for being in rescue: The first time here, Lacey was found as a stray in NC and landed at a shelter. We placed her (see above) and she returned due to the health of her owner. 
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Lacey had mammary tumors removed in March 2018 when she was spayed. She had a dental when she came back to us as sadly dental care had been neglected. She lost several teeth.  Lacey does not appear to hear well.  Like many ladies "of a certain age" Lacey does need to have access to the facilities frequently. There is no physical reason for her frequent bathroom trips, it's just part of who she is (and we ladies understand about older bladders!). Lacey is a senior girl.  Her mammary tumors have returned, but given her age and overall condition we do not recommend surgery. Her rear left leg gives her issues and at times she will not use it. She has responded well to pain medicine. Again, given her age any sort of surgical intervention is not recommended.
Weight: 14 lbs
Height: 12 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $1 - and donations gratefully accepted

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Lacey is a sweet, quiet girl. She is looking for a quiet home where she can be someone's quiet companion. Lacey will be happy as the only dog in a home or in a house with another quiet dog. She is indifferent to cats. Lacey has never lived with children. Lacey is looking for a quiet home that will offer her end of life comfort and care. We imagine this beautiful girl has quite the bucket list and is eager to live it out!

What is my personality like? Lacey is an absolute sweetheart. She loves to cuddle and play. Lacey is more of a couch potato and loves to snuggle in blankets - she can wrap herself up like a burrito!  She's great with other dogs but doesn't really play; she prefers to watch everyone else. 

Lacey isn't real big on basic obedience cues like sit or stay but I think part of this is her hearing.  She is very attuned to visual and can see and smell a treat from a long ways off.  With a little patience and plenty of attention this little girl is really going to thrive. Lacey would be fine in a house with other animals.

Lacey is a quiet girl that sleeps a lot. She is looking for her hospice home.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Curious and gentle

Other tips and tidbits: Lacey's estimated birthday is 2/24/2009

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained.  A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Lucas is a sweet boy. His approximate birth date is 4/2010.  He gets along with cats and dogs. He isn't much for being held, but does love face pets. He is always just hangin in the room, like a quiet companion. Lucas has no teeth, but gets along just fine with dry food. He has never been aggressive with his claws. He enjoys playing with other playful cats, and likes to run around the house, or play tag with others. He will take a while to get settled once he finds his forever home. Patience will be required. RJ came to us from Texas and he was quickly adopted. Unfortunately, his owners have fallen on hard times and are left with no other option than to return RJ to us. Rj is now 5 1/2 years old, weighs 16 pounds and is a Chihuahua/Dachshund mix.

RJ has your typical Chihuahua personality - he loves his people and wants to be a cuddle bug, but isn't the biggest fan of strangers. RJ would love a quiet home as he is a low energy, mellow guy that does well with his immediate family! 

If you are interested in RJ, visit EHRDOGS.ORG and fill out an application for RJ LONESTAR!!!!!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Cloud, about 4 years old, is a Boxer mix rescued from a North Carolina kill shelter, emaciated and suffering from a life of neglect. She is a beautiful little petite pixie - 40 pounds of dynamite: a big personality in a small package!  She's a total love bug and very affectionate with her people. She's  house trained, crate trained, has great leash manners and knows basic commands. Extremely smart, Cloud learns quickly and is eager to please. A high- energy girl, she requires daily exercise and stimulation. A fenced-in yard is a must.  She is very dog-selective and although she tends to do  well with large dominant male dogs who offer correction and leadership, she's not a fan of other females, and has a high prey drive, so no small dogs or cats for Cloud, thank you! She must have a strong and confident leader. She is an absolute JOY, but not for a first-time dog owner or novice handler. She requires patience, direction and a family who will set her up for success and be vigilant in keeping her from bad situations. Her foster parents have worked with her on some food guarding tendencies, which result from her hungry times on the streets.  Cloud's home must be exceptional because she is an exceptional girl!  S he  is spayed and up to date on vaccines. If you would like to be the lucky one who gets to give Cloud her happy ever after, please fill out an adoption application here: http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org/general-application 

RDR's adoption fees include the cost of spay/neuter/microchip at an RDR-approved facility, whether completed before adoption or if deferred because the pet is too young or has a medical issue.  All pets are also current on age-appropriate vaccines at the time of adoption

Given technical constraints on this database, this pet's location may not be as listed here. We can, however, provide transport support for pets in foster at a considerable distance from the adopter.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Sacramento- Squish came to us originally as a baby,  when this litter of puppies was left in a tub outside of a spay and neuter clinic.  He was barely four weeks old and required formula in addition to watered down canned food.  He had a head injury and we were not sure he would survive, but he kept fighting and within a matter of a month, he was the same as his three siblings.  Squish was adopted when he was about three months old, but when he was about 6 months old, he started to exhibit anxious behaviors.  Rather than work with him and a trainer, his adoptive family decided to return him.  When Squish came back to us, he was a bit of a mess.  He did not trust strangers at all, and he would not go into a crate.  We were able to work through a lot of his fears and he was crate trained once again. He learned basic obedience, but he continued to live with extremely high anxiety.  We had Squish evaluated and made the decision to try prozac.  It took a couple months to figure out his correct dose, but he was suddenly a more relaxed version of himself, and he was much happier.  Squish continues to take prozac, which is minimal in cost (he will be sent to his new home with quite a bit, too).

 

Squish then participated in a board and train program for a couple weeks to work on his lack of confidence.  He has improved quite a bit, but he continues to require to proper introductions to new people and situations, and really would prefer a quiet home without children, so he can be his best, most relaxed self.  He is not a coffee shop dog, he does not need fieldtrips and outtings.  He is most happy at home, with his people.  He LOVES balls.  Fetch, soccer, and more. Anything for a chance to play with big rubber balls.  He does not really understand tug-of-war, he would much rather fetch a ball or kick it around.  

 

Yes, Squish is nervous and takes time to warm up, but once he does, he will be your biggest admirer and your best friend. He is worth the patience and time and love to build his trust, because he is the sweetest boy to ever be, and is 95 lbs of dopey love.  Also, he has the cutest little docked knub (he came that way, at just 4 weeks) and it wiggles so fast when he is happy! It is worth everything to see that.

 

He is neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines. 

 

If interested, you can go online and find our adoption process and apply online at:     http://recycledpetsnorcal.org/adoptpet/

 

Adoption fee: $200

He is also has no problem with cat friendly dogs.

He will make a truly wonderful companion and is every bit the dapper gentle cat that he looks. You gotta love that little milk moustache!

NAME: Precious
BREED: Chihuahua
BIRTHDAY: 2004
WEIGHT: 10lbs

 

Precious is a fun little piglet who has adjusted beautifully to life in her busy foster home. She is a very old lady who has been with us about four years. Because she is so happy here and because she as been here for such a long time, we feel it is best for her if she stays for whatever time she has left.
 
Of course, doing what is right for Precious is not the easiest choice for our little rescue. The cost of food, medications, and diabetic supplies add up each month, but we are committed to giving all of our fosters the best life possible. For Precious, that means staying here... so that's what we'll do. Please consider making a donation for Precious' ongoing care!

Tony came to us from local shelter. He is very in-tune to his people. He gets along with other pups and enjoys a good romp and playtime. Tony is making progress with his manners, and is generally an easy keeper! At 6 years, Tony is still quite an active boy, athletic and agile, making him an ideal candidate for a running or walking buddy. He can be a rascal around cats (the chase is just too much fun to resist) so a no-cat home would be best!

While Tony adores attention from the kiddos, he’s not quite aware of his own exuberance, and would be a better fit for a home with older, respectful children. Tony has waited a long time for a forever home. We know his his family is out there, just waiting to connect!

As his foster family, we will miss him!  We would love to hear how he is doing should you choose to add Tony to your family, and send updates!

I am told I am quite a looker. I am here because life got in the way and my family could no longer keep me. I am definitely a people person and need to be your whole world, so a home with no other dogs or children is where I will do best. I still have a great deal of energy so I will need a couple of walks a day, but not too long, as I am an adult heading into my senior years. After our walks you can expect my 80 pounds of goofy love to snuggle in your lap or at least give it a really good try.

PLEASE NOTE: Because we require home checks, adoptions are restricted to the Los Angeles area.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Bailey  is a 2.5 year-old Maltese mix .  He was surrendered  because  his owner  was not prepared for the energy of a young puppy .  He is all legs and is still like a gangly Colt at this point.  He's very kissy and huggable once he gets to know you,  but he also has lots of energy and so will need a fenced-in backyard.  Bailey is not good with children, so he would be best in a home with adults and no kids under 13.  He weighs 15 pounds. He is house trained (not perfect) and crate trained. Alcovy dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on all vaccines, up to date on heart-worm preventative and flea preventative and micro-chipped.
If interested in adoption, please complete an online application on Alcovy Pet Rescue's website at www.alcovypet.com. You must have a vet reference to adopt. We verify the care of past/current pets. Applications without a vet reference will not be approved for adoption. Our goal is to have the very best home for all our dogs and cats and therefore we reserve the right to approve or deny an application based on what we determine is in the pet's best interest.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Atlas Maverick was adopted from us when he was only 2 months old, but was returned after less than a year in the home because they didn't have the time to train or play with him, and the poor pup was spending more and more time crated. Toward the end of his time there, we don't think he was cared for well at all.

Maverick, as his kennel friends call him, was very scared when he found himself back with EHR.  Our staff and volunteers have been working with him, but it is not the same as being in a home. He needs slow introductions to people, because he lost his trust in his humans at such a young age. This boy would need a quiet, adult only house where he can learn to relax. He needs someone who will take it slow and build his trust again. He has not had good experiences with cats or small dogs, but having another canine companion who is well balanced and can be a good influence will help give Maverick the confidence he needs. He must be in a home with another dog.

Maverick is house & crate trained, plus he walks well on a leash. With his friends, he is a young boy who loves to play with toys & a game of "Fetch" if you're up for it. He is smart & knows basic commands. He would do best in a home with people who are active & have dog experience. 

Can you be the one to give this big guy the place he needs to feel loved and protected?  Give him a chance to show you what kind of dog he can be with the right kind of owner! Please fill out an application today at www.ehrdogs.org & be sure to ask for him by name, ATLAS MAVERICK SCAS!
